

User request flow:
A user types www.foobar.com in the browser.
The browser asks DNS to translate www.foobar.com into an IP address.
The domain foobar.com has a www DNS record that points to the server IP address 8.8.8.8.
After getting the IP address, the user browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request to the server.
The server uses TCP/IP to communicate with the user's computer.

Infrastructure:

User
  |
  v
DNS: www.foobar.com -> 8.8.8.8
  |
  v
Server: 8.8.8.8
  |
  |-- Nginx web server
  |-- Application server
  |-- Application files / codebase
  |-- MySQL database

Explanation:

A server is a physical or virtual machine that provides services or resources to other computers called clients.

The role of the domain name is to give users a human-readable name instead of making them remember the server IP address.

The www in www.foobar.com is a DNS record. It is usually a CNAME record if it points to another domain name, or an A record if it points directly to an IP address. In this infrastructure, www points to 8.8.8.8, so it is an A record.

The role of the web server, Nginx, is to receive HTTP/HTTPS requests from users and serve static content or forward dynamic requests to the application server.

The role of the application server is to run the application logic and generate dynamic content using the application codebase.

The application files, also called the codebase, contain the source code of the website or web application.

The role of the database, MySQL, is to store and manage the website data, such as users, posts, products, or settings.

The server communicates with the user's computer using TCP/IP over the network. For web traffic, it uses HTTP or HTTPS.

Issues with this infrastructure:

1. Single Point of Failure:
There is only one server. If the server goes down, the whole website becomes unavailable.

2. Downtime during maintenance:
If we need to deploy new code, restart Nginx, restart the application server, or update the database, the website may be unavailable during that time.

3. Cannot scale well:
All components are on one server. If traffic increases too much, the server may become slow or crash because there is no load balancer and no additional servers.
